PROMPT stack_heap_memory_comparison
WITH BUDGET 6000 tokens
USING MODEL "claude-sonnet-4-5"

SELECT
    system_role("You are a computer systems expert specializing in memory management, system programming, and computer architecture with deep knowledge of stack and heap memory allocation mechanisms.")

GENERATE
    compare_memory_allocation("Explain the fundamental differences between stack and heap memory allocation, covering: the definition of stack memory as a LIFO (Last In, First Out) data structure used for automatic memory allocation with function calls and local variables, versus heap memory as a pool of memory used for dynamic allocation where memory blocks can be allocated and freed in any order, key structural differences including how stack memory is managed automatically by the compiler and runtime system with strict ordering constraints, while heap memory requires explicit allocation and deallocation by the programmer or garbage collector, performance characteristics where stack allocation is extremely fast (just moving a stack pointer) with O(1) allocation/deallocation time, while heap allocation is slower due to searching for suitable memory blocks and managing fragmentation, memory layout differences showing how stack grows downward from high memory addresses with automatic cleanup when functions return, versus heap memory scattered throughout available address space with potential fragmentation, scope and lifetime differences where stack variables are automatically destroyed when leaving scope, while heap-allocated memory persists until explicitly freed, size limitations with stack having limited size (typically a few MB) leading to stack overflow for deep recursion or large local arrays, while heap is limited only by available system memory, practical usage patterns including when to use stack for local variables, function parameters, and return addresses versus heap for dynamic data structures, large objects, and data that must persist beyond function scope, common issues like stack overflow from excessive recursion or large local arrays, heap fragmentation reducing available memory, memory leaks from unreleased heap memory, and dangling pointers to freed heap memory, with concrete examples in C/C++ showing stack allocation syntax versus malloc/new for heap allocation.")
WITH OUTPUT BUDGET 3000 tokens, TEMPERATURE 0.2, FORMAT markdown;